context about programs in India, Kenya, the United States, Mexico, Nicaragua, Zimbabwe, and South Africa. Women's Empowerment and Global Health provides the next generation of researchers and practitioners, as well as students in global and public health, sociology, anthropology, women's studies, law, business, and medicine, with cutting-edge and inspirational examples of programs that point the way toward achieving women's equality and the positive outcome of empowerment on health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMedical policyvCase studies. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienevCase studies. 0aWomenxPolitical activityvCross-cultural studies. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsvCase studies. 0aWomen's rightsvCase studies. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh1 aDworkin, Shari, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGandhi, Monica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPassano, Paige, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520962729423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520962729.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles